{"title_page": "Wendy Turner Webster", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image       = \n| caption     =\n| name        = Wendy Turner-Webster\n| birthname   = Wendy Turner\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1967|06|05|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Stoke-on-Trent]], [[Staffordshire]], England\n| occupation  = [[Journalist]], [[television presenter]] \n| spouse      = [[Gary Webster (actor)|Gary Webster]]\n| children    = Jack and Freddie\n| residence   = \n| website     = \n| credits     = \n}}\n'''Wendy Turner-Webster''' (born '''Wendy Turner''', 5 June 1967) is an [[English people|English]] [[journalist]], [[television presenter]] and [[animal welfare]] campaigner.\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn 5 June 1967 in [[Stoke-on-Trent]], [[Staffordshire]], Turner-Webster had two sisters, presenter [[Anthea Turner]] and Ruth who had [[spina bifida]] and died at the age of 15. Turner-Webster grew up in [[Norton le Moors]], Staffordshire, and was educated at St Dominic\u2019s Independent Junior School at [[Hartshill]].\n\n==Career==\nTurner-Webster began her career at [[Signal Radio]], writing, producing and presenting on-air features including film, travel and book reviews.<ref name=TISBio>{{citeweb|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/wendywebsterturner.html|title=Wendy Turner Webster|publisher=This is Staffordshire|date=2009-02-02|accessdate=2010-01-10|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100328010352/http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/wendywebsterturner.html|archivedate=2010-03-28}}</ref>  She also wrote for magazines including [[OK!]]. A part-time actress, while appearing in the [[pantomime]] ''[[Cinderella]],'' she was spotted by a producer from the UK cable channel ''[[L!VE TV]].''<ref name=TISBio/> Moving to [[London]], she became a news reporter covering sports and fashion. She then hosted her own shows ''Videobox'' and the [[psychic]] phone-in ''Revelations with Nina.''\n\nTurner-Webster was chosen to take over hosting [[Channel 4]]\u2019s ''Absolutely Animals'' from [[Dani Behr]];<ref name=TISBio/> the show was a forerunner to ''[[Pet Rescue (TV series)|Pet Rescue]]'' which Turner-Webster hosted for 7 years.<ref name=TISBio/> Turner-Webster's other TV projects include [[BBC One]]'s ''Your Kids Are In Charge'', presented with sister Anthea. She has also presented several episodes of ''The Last Word'' for [[Central Independent Television|Central Television]], and the BBC documentary about domestic violence, ''Hitting Home.''\n\n==Animal welfare==\nTurner-Webster does not eat or wear animal products and is Patron of the [[Vegan|Vegan Society]], [[Vegetarians' International Voice for Animals|Viva!]] and [[the Vegetarian Society]].<ref name=TISBio/> In 2001, Turner-Webster wrote on behalf of [[PETA]] to the [[Duke of Kent]] as president of [[the Scout Association]], requesting that they retire the angling badge on grounds of cruelty to animals. The proposal was rejected.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fishing.co.uk/article.php3?id=717 |title=Freedom and the price of Fishing |website=Fishing.co.uk |date=31 May 2001 |author=M. A. Roe |accessdate=24 January 2017}}</ref> In 2006, she launched an on-line footwear company, \"Secret Goddess\", which specialised in ultra glamorous boots and shoes of non-animal origin.\n\nIn November 2010, she became the patron of Chancepixies Animal Rescue, a charity dedicated to educating, rescuing and taking action to prevent dogs in the UK from finding themselves unwanted, abused and killed.<ref>[http://www.ourdogs.co.uk/News/2010/Nov2010/News261110/animal.htm Animal rescue continues fight to change UK dog laws<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n<ref>[http://www.thisiskent.co.uk/news/Star-backs-change-dog-laws/article-2927060-detail/article.html ANIMAL rights campaigner Wendy Turner-Webster has backed a West Hougham animal rescue centre's fight to change Britain's dog laws.]</ref>\n<ref>[http://www.chancepixies.com/latest_news.htm#wendy Chancepixies Animal Rescue<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nTurner-Webster's first marriage in her early 20s broke down as a result of [[domestic violence]]. She now speaks on domestic violence issues on behalf of various causes.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/home/you/article-1241325/Reese-Witherspoon-men-marriage.html|title='Stuff happens with men and marriage' - Reese Witherspoon on her toughest role ever|publisher=daily Mail|date=2010-01-10|accessdate=2010-01-10}}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=yes|date=September 2019}}\n\nWhilst playing [[Maid Marian]] in pantomime, Turner-Webster met and began a relationship with actor [[Gary Webster (actor)|Gary Webster]], who starred in ''[[Family Affairs]].'' They married in 1999 and have two sons, Jack and Freddie. \n\nAn interview article in the Daily Mail on 13 July 2019 referred to Wendy and Gary having been virtually destitute and being homeless at one point (living in family car and travel lodges). However at the time of the article the family were now living in a rented home.  The family lives in [[Surrey]].<ref name=TISBio/>\n\n==Filmography==\n* You Do Too - 2002, TV series, pre\n* [[Robot Wars (TV series)|Robot Wars]] - 2000, presenter, contestant on Celebrity Special as Gemini\n* Your Kids Are In Charge - 2000 for BBC. Co-presenter with sister Anthea\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{imdb name|id=0877935|name=Wendy Turner-Webster}}\n* [https://thespeakersagency.com/speaker/wendy-turner-webster Wendy Turner Webster profile at The Speakers Agency]\n\n{{Animal rights}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Turner-Webster, Wendy}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Stoke-on-Trent]]\n[[Category:English television presenters]]\n[[Category:People associated with animal welfare and rights]]\n[[Category:Veganism activists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image       = \n| caption     =\n| name        = Wendy Turner-Webster\n| birthname   = Wendy Turner\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1967|06|05|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Stoke-on-Trent]], [[Staffordshire]], England\n| occupation  = [[Journalist]], [[television presenter]] \n| spouse      = [[Gary Webster]]\n| children    = Jack and Freddie\n| residence   = \n| website     = \n| credits     = \n}}\n'''Wendy Turner-Webster''' (born '''Wendy Turner''', 5 June 1967) is an [[English people|English]] [[journalist]], [[television presenter]] and [[animal welfare]] campaigner.\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn 5 June 1967 in [[Stoke-on-Trent]], [[Staffordshire]], Turner-Webster had two sisters, presenter [[Anthea Turner]] and Ruth who had [[spina bifida]] and died at the age of 15. Turner-Webster grew up in [[Norton le Moors]], Staffordshire, and was educated at St Dominic\u2019s Independent Junior School at [[Hartshill]].\n\n==Career==\nTurner-Webster began her career at [[Signal Radio]], writing, producing and presenting on-air features including film, travel and book reviews.<ref name=TISBio>{{citeweb|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/wendywebsterturner.html|title=Wendy Turner Webster|publisher=This is Staffordshire|date=2009-02-02|accessdate=2010-01-10|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100328010352/http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/wendywebsterturner.html|archivedate=2010-03-28}}</ref>  She also wrote for magazines including [[OK!]]. A part-time actress, while appearing in the [[pantomime]] ''[[Cinderella]],'' she was spotted by a producer from the UK cable channel ''[[L!VE TV]].''<ref name=TISBio/> Moving to [[London]], she became a news reporter covering sports and fashion. She then hosted her own shows ''Videobox'' and the [[psychic]] phone-in ''Revelations with Nina.''\n\nTurner-Webster was chosen to take over hosting [[Channel 4]]\u2019s ''Absolutely Animals'' from [[Dani Behr]];<ref name=TISBio/> the show was a forerunner to ''[[Pet Rescue (TV series)|Pet Rescue]]'' which Turner-Webster hosted for 7 years.<ref name=TISBio/> Turner-Webster's other TV projects include [[BBC One]]'s ''Your Kids Are In Charge'', presented with sister Anthea. She has also presented several episodes of ''The Last Word'' for [[Central Independent Television|Central Television]], and the BBC documentary about domestic violence, ''Hitting Home.''\n\n==Animal welfare==\nTurner-Webster does not eat or wear animal products and is Patron of the [[Vegan|Vegan Society]], [[Vegetarians' International Voice for Animals|Viva!]] and [[the Vegetarian Society]].<ref name=TISBio/> In 2001, Turner-Webster wrote on behalf of [[PETA]] to the [[Duke of Kent]] as president of [[the Scout Association]], requesting that they retire the angling badge on grounds of cruelty to animals. The proposal was rejected.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fishing.co.uk/article.php3?id=717 |title=Freedom and the price of Fishing |website=Fishing.co.uk |date=31 May 2001 |author=M. A. Roe |accessdate=24 January 2017}}</ref> In 2006, she launched an on-line footwear company, \"Secret Goddess\", which specialised in ultra glamorous boots and shoes of non-animal origin.\n\nIn November 2010, she became the patron of Chancepixies Animal Rescue, a charity dedicated to educating, rescuing and taking action to prevent dogs in the UK from finding themselves unwanted, abused and killed.<ref>[http://www.ourdogs.co.uk/News/2010/Nov2010/News261110/animal.htm Animal rescue continues fight to change UK dog laws<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n<ref>[http://www.thisiskent.co.uk/news/Star-backs-change-dog-laws/article-2927060-detail/article.html ANIMAL rights campaigner Wendy Turner-Webster has backed a West Hougham animal rescue centre's fight to change Britain's dog laws.]</ref>\n<ref>[http://www.chancepixies.com/latest_news.htm#wendy Chancepixies Animal Rescue<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nTurner-Webster's first marriage in her early 20s broke down as a result of [[domestic violence]]. She now speaks on domestic violence issues on behalf of various causes.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/home/you/article-1241325/Reese-Witherspoon-men-marriage.html|title='Stuff happens with men and marriage' - Reese Witherspoon on her toughest role ever|publisher=daily Mail|date=2010-01-10|accessdate=2010-01-10}}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=yes|date=September 2019}}\n\nWhilst playing [[Maid Marian]] in pantomime, Turner-Webster met and began a relationship with actor [[Gary Webster]], who starred in ''[[Family Affairs]].'' They married in 1999 and have two sons, Jack and Freddie. \n\nAn interview article in the Daily Mail on 13 July 2019 referred to Wendy and Gary having been virtually destitute and being homeless at one point (living in family car and travel lodges). However at the time of the article the family were now living in a rented home.  The family lives in [[Surrey]].<ref name=TISBio/>\n\n==Filmography==\n* You Do Too - 2002, TV series, pre\n* [[Robot Wars (TV series)|Robot Wars]] - 2000, presenter, contestant on Celebrity Special as Gemini\n* Your Kids Are In Charge - 2000 for BBC. Co-presenter with sister Anthea\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{imdb name|id=0877935|name=Wendy Turner-Webster}}\n* [https://thespeakersagency.com/speaker/wendy-turner-webster Wendy Turner Webster profile at The Speakers Agency]\n\n{{Animal rights}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Turner-Webster, Wendy}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Stoke-on-Trent]]\n[[Category:English television presenters]]\n[[Category:People associated with animal welfare and rights]]\n[[Category:Veganism activists]]\n", "name_user": "Tassedethe", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Repaired 1 link to disambiguation page -(You can help)-Gary Webster", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wendy_Turner_Webster"}
{"title_page": "Tony Hall (supervisor)", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=April 2011}}{{Infobox Politician\n| name                = Tony Hall\n| image               = Tony HALL, 12Jan01.jpg\n}}\n\n'''Anthony Hall''' (born 1942) is former American elected official. He was a [[Members of the San Francisco Board of Supervisors|member]] of the [[San Francisco]] [[San Francisco Board of Supervisors|Board of Supervisors]] from 2000 to 2004.<ref name=\"RamakrishnanBloemraad2008\">{{cite book|last1=Ramakrishnan|first1=Subramanian Karthick|last2=Bloemraad|first2=Irene|title=Civic hopes and political realities: immigrants, community organizations, and political engagement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=woFWKhnAJGMC&pg=PA344|accessdate=16 April 2011|year=2008|publisher=Russell Sage Foundation|isbn=978-0-87154-701-9|page=344}}</ref> He resigned in 2004 to accept appointment as executive director of the [[Treasure Island (California)|Treasure Island]] Development Authority,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2005-10-10/bay-area/17393277_1_treasure-island-development-authority-city-hall-mayor-s-office|title=Treasure Island's big developer slams Tony Hall|last=Matier|first=Phillip|author2=Andrew Ross |date=10 October 2005|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|accessdate=16 April 2011}}</ref> a post he held for only 14 months. Hall later filed papers for running against the incumbent Newsom in the [[San Francisco mayoral election, 2007|2007 mayoral election]] but dropped out before the election, citing Newsom's entrenchment.\nHe was known as the lone conservative on the Board of Supervisors and surprised the other board members when he supported [[Matt Gonzalez]]'s successful bid for president of the board.\n\n== Early life ==\nBorn in Los Angeles, Hall attended Loyola High School and graduated from UCLA with a degree in economics and public administration. He moved to San Francisco in 1964.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lelchuk|first=Ilene|url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2001-02-06/news/17585618_1_irish-american-wedding-singer-political-appointees|title=Gonzalez calls the mayor a liar / Brown denies he said candidate is a racist|date=6 February 2001|work=The San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref> His volunteer and civic activities have included singing Mass at St. Brendan's Church on Sundays,<ref name=\"Lelchuk\" /> volunteering as a track coach at St. Ignatius Prep School,<ref name=\"Lelchuk\" /> and announcing the San Francisco\u2019s St. Patrick's Day Parade.<ref name=\"Lelchuk\" />\n\nHall and his band \u201cThe Hallmarks\u201d perform at weddings and are a mainstay of the San Francisco music scene.<ref name=\"Lelchuk\" />\n\n== Career ==\nHe is a former Executive Assistant to the Presiding Judge of the [[San Francisco Superior Court]].{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n\n=== San Francisco Board of Supervisors ===\nIn 2000, Hall was elected to represent District 7 on the San Francisco Board of Supervisors.<ref name=\"sfbos.org\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sfbos.org/ftp/uploadedfiles/bdsupvrs/resolutions04/r0532-04.pdf}}</ref>\n\nThe San Francisco Chronicle said of Hall at the time: \u201cHall's politics are old-school San Francisco, and he plans to keep it that way.\u201d The Chronicle described Hall as \u201cfocused on neighborhoods the same way that supervisors were in the late 1970s during the city's first attempt at district elections.\u201d<ref name=\"Lelchuk\">{{cite news|title=A New Song Tony Hall has brought a booming voice and feisty energy to the S.F. Board of Supervisors|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2001/02/06/MN100340.DTL&ao=2|newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle|date=February 6, 2001|first=Ilene|last=Lelchuk}}</ref> He was praised unanimously in a resolution by his colleagues calling Hall \u201ca dedicated legislator serving with integrity, intelligence, and a willingness to work with all parties for the common good of the City.\u201d<ref name=\"sfbos.org\"/>\n\nAs a Supervisor, Hall was involved in the following issues:\n\n* he led the restoration/renovation of the Harding Park Golf Course, resulting in the acquisition of annual PGA tournaments, which have provided the City with millions in revenue.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2002-04-09/bay-area/17539964_1_tee-times-san-franciscans-harding | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | first=Rachel | last=Gordon | title=Supervisors see election results as sign of support | date=9 April 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2002-03-28/sports/17535579_1_harding-park-new-plan-approved | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | first=Brian | last=Murphy | title=New and Improved Golf Courses Are Springing Up / Renovating Harding Park could bring PGA Tour in 2002 | date=28 March 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2002/04/07/SP222774.DTL | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | first=Brian | last=Murphy | title=Harding Park bill clearing final hurdles -- maybe | date=6 September 2010}}</ref>\n* he introduced and passed legislation for the re-build of Laguna Honda Home for the aged.<ref name=\"sfbos.org\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfbos.org/index.aspx?page=1463}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2002-08-13/bay-area/17558362_1_twin-peaks-fund-construction-supervisors | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | first=Rachel | last=Gordon | title=SF Supervisorial Candidates: District 7 | date=13 August 2002}}</ref>\n* he spearheaded the reconstruction of the Ocean Avenue commercial district.<ref name=\"sfbos.org\"/>\n* he led the renewal and reconstruction of the City\u2019s Youth Guidance Center.<ref name=\"sfbos.org\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfrichmondreview.com/archives/richmondreview/2002editions/July02/hallcol.html}}</ref>\n* he worked with state and local agencies and private entities to solve the Lake Merced water loss/level problem.<ref name=\"sfbos.org\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2002/07/07/SP224336.DTL | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | first=Tom | last=Stienstra | title=The fine print behind Lake Merced agreement | date=5 September 2010}}</ref>\n* he led the restoration and beautification of the City\u2019s Great Highway and the adjoining Ocean Beach.<ref name=\"sfbos.org\"/>\n* he preserved and initiated maintenance for parks and open spaces, including the building of sports fields, and incorporated after-school recreational and educational programs for youth.<ref name=\"sfbos.org\"/>\n* he implemented programs within his district to calm traffic in conjunction with street beautification projects.<ref name=\"sfbos.org\"/>\n* his \u201cBlueprint for Homeless Reform Policy\u201d, introduced in 2001, was the product of a 15-year personal study which encompassed a 7-point package of ordinances and resolutions which established quality of life and civility laws and mandated policy changes within the homeless industry.  Hall directly questioned the efficacy of then-Supervisor Gavin Newsom\u2019s \u201cCare-Not-Cash\u201d initiative.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hpn.asu.edu/archives/2002-January/005342.html}}</ref>\n* he implemented the Safely Surrendered Baby Law (Senate Bill 1368) for San Francisco and passed the Safe Haven for Newborns legislation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfbos.org/ftp/uploadedfiles/bdsupvrs/resolutions02/r0615-02.pdf}}</ref>\n\n=== Treasure Island Development Authority ===\nHall served on the Board of Supervisors until August 2004,<ref>{{cite news|title=Board gives maverick Hall a fond farewell|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2004/08/20/WBGFF86G8P1.DTL|newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle | first=Rachel|last=Gordon|date=31 August 2010}}</ref> when Mayor Gavin Newsom asked Hall to assume the post of Executive Director of the Treasure Island Development Authority. Mayor Newsom publicly stated that his choice was due to Hall's record of accomplishments in the area of public facilities and special projects.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2004/08/01/BAGD68104S1.DTL | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | first=Rachel | last=Gordon | title=SAN FRANCISCO / Newsom confirms he wants Hall for job / 2 panels must OK supervisor to run Treasure Island | date=2 September 2010}}</ref> Newsom appointed [[Sean Elsbernd]] to replace Hall on the Board of Supervisors.\n\nHall conducted on-going meetings with the developer regarding plans and contract compliance issues, as well as parallel interaction with the United States Navy principals responsible for re-conveyance of the property to San Francisco. The Navy had become skeptical of San Francisco's sincerity and the ability of the developer to issue a concrete redevelopment plan after more than seven years. Newsom insisted upon a renewal of the developer's contract, despite the fact that the developer had not met its terms; there were substantial payment shortfalls for specific developmental milestones, and a series of discarded timetable extensions. Newsom also insisted that other \u201cpartners\u201d be allowed to join the development team without going through the public bidding process as mandated by the City Charter.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2005/09/27/BAG4OEUHMT1.DTL | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | first=Charlie | last=Goodyear | title=SAN FRANCISCO / Treasure Island chief decries development delay | date=29 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2005, the Treasure Island Development Authority voted to require the resignation of Tony Hall from the project \u201cwithout cause.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fogcityjournal.com/news_in_brief/hall_fired_051012.shtml}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2005-10-13/bay-area/17395876_1_island-s-board-treasure-island-development-authority-city-hall | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | first=Cecilia M. | last=Vega | title=SAN FRANCISCO / Treasure Island chief may lose job in vote set today / Newsom speaks to board of directors about his concerns | date=13 October 2005}}</ref> Hall subsequently warned of the dangers of development on Treasure Island, calling it a \u201cseismically unsafe toxic landfill\u201d on top of the San Andreas fault.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/22/us/22bcintel.html?_r=2 | work=The New York Times | first=Hank | last=Pellissier | title=Local Intelligence \u2013 Building 1 | date=21 August 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Other work ===\nSince departing Treasure Island, Hall has maintained a blog on issues related to civic life in San Francisco, and is a columnist for the Westside Observer.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tonyhallsf.wordpress.com/}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Hall began a campaign for San Francisco mayor to challenge Newsom, but dropped out.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ebar.com/news/article.php?sec=news&article=2114}}</ref> In March 2011, Hall announced he was running for mayor a second time,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfexaminer.com/blogs/under-dome/2010/12/tony-hall-tweets-his-intent-run-mayor}}</ref> but his bid was unsuccessful.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.tonyhallsf.com/ Campaign website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off|us}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Members of the San Francisco Board of Supervisors|Member of the San Francisco Board of Supervisors<br>District 7]] | before=District Created | after=[[Sean Elsbernd]] | years=2000&ndash;2004}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hall, Tony}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:San Francisco Board of Supervisors members]]\n[[Category:University of California, Los Angeles alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=April 2011}}\n'''Anthony Hall''' (born 1942) was a candidate for [[Mayor of San Francisco]] and a [[Members of the San Francisco Board of Supervisors|member]] (2000\u20132004) of the [[San Francisco]] [[San Francisco Board of Supervisors|Board of Supervisors]].<ref name=\"RamakrishnanBloemraad2008\">{{cite book|last1=Ramakrishnan|first1=Subramanian Karthick|last2=Bloemraad|first2=Irene|title=Civic hopes and political realities: immigrants, community organizations, and political engagement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=woFWKhnAJGMC&pg=PA344|accessdate=16 April 2011|year=2008|publisher=Russell Sage Foundation|isbn=978-0-87154-701-9|page=344}}</ref> He resigned in 2004 to accept appointment as executive director of the [[Treasure Island (California)|Treasure Island]] Development Authority,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2005-10-10/bay-area/17393277_1_treasure-island-development-authority-city-hall-mayor-s-office|title=Treasure Island's big developer slams Tony Hall|last=Matier|first=Phillip|author2=Andrew Ross |date=10 October 2005|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|accessdate=16 April 2011}}</ref> a post he held for only 14 months.\n[[Image:Tony HALL, 12Jan01.jpg|thumb|Tony Hall]]\nHe was known as the lone conservative on the Board of Supervisors, and surprised the other board members when he supported [[Matt Gonzalez]]'s successful bid for president of the board.\n\nHall later filed papers for running against the incumbent Newsom in the [[San Francisco mayoral election, 2007|2007 mayoral election]], but dropped out before the election, citing Newsom's entrenchment.\n\nHe is also a former Executive Assistant to the Presiding Judge of the [[San Francisco Superior Court]].{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n\n==Public service==\nIn 2000, Hall was elected to represent District 7 on the San Francisco the Board of Supervisors.<ref name=\"sfbos.org\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sfbos.org/ftp/uploadedfiles/bdsupvrs/resolutions04/r0532-04.pdf}}</ref>\n\nThe San Francisco Chronicle said of Hall at the time: \u201cHall's politics are old-school San Francisco, and he plans to keep it that way.\u201d The Chronicle described Hall as \u201cfocused on neighborhoods the same way that supervisors were in the late 1970s during the city's first attempt at district elections.\u201d<ref name=\"Lelchuk\">{{cite news|title=A New Song Tony Hall has brought a booming voice and feisty energy to the S.F. Board of Supervisors|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2001/02/06/MN100340.DTL&ao=2|newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle|date=February 6, 2001|first=Ilene|last=Lelchuk}}</ref> He was praised unanimously in a resolution by his colleagues calling Hall \u201ca dedicated legislator serving with integrity, intelligence, and a willingness to work with all parties for the common good of the City.\u201d<ref name=\"sfbos.org\"/>\n\nAs a Supervisor, Hall was involved in the following issues:\n\n* he led the restoration/renovation of the Harding Park Golf Course, resulting in the acquisition of annual PGA tournaments, which have provided the City with millions in revenue.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2002-04-09/bay-area/17539964_1_tee-times-san-franciscans-harding | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | first=Rachel | last=Gordon | title=Supervisors see election results as sign of support | date=9 April 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2002-03-28/sports/17535579_1_harding-park-new-plan-approved | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | first=Brian | last=Murphy | title=New and Improved Golf Courses Are Springing Up / Renovating Harding Park could bring PGA Tour in 2002 | date=28 March 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2002/04/07/SP222774.DTL | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | first=Brian | last=Murphy | title=Harding Park bill clearing final hurdles -- maybe | date=6 September 2010}}</ref>\n* he introduced and passed legislation for the re-build of Laguna Honda Home for the aged.<ref name=\"sfbos.org\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfbos.org/index.aspx?page=1463}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2002-08-13/bay-area/17558362_1_twin-peaks-fund-construction-supervisors | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | first=Rachel | last=Gordon | title=SF Supervisorial Candidates: District 7 | date=13 August 2002}}</ref>\n* he spearheaded the reconstruction of the Ocean Avenue commercial district.<ref name=\"sfbos.org\"/>\n* he led the renewal and reconstruction of the City\u2019s Youth Guidance Center.<ref name=\"sfbos.org\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfrichmondreview.com/archives/richmondreview/2002editions/July02/hallcol.html}}</ref>\n* he worked with state and local agencies and private entities to solve the Lake Merced water loss/level problem.<ref name=\"sfbos.org\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2002/07/07/SP224336.DTL | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | first=Tom | last=Stienstra | title=The fine print behind Lake Merced agreement | date=5 September 2010}}</ref>\n* he led the restoration and beautification of the City\u2019s Great Highway and the adjoining Ocean Beach.<ref name=\"sfbos.org\"/>\n* he preserved and initiated maintenance for parks and open spaces, including the building of sports fields, and incorporated after-school recreational and educational programs for youth.<ref name=\"sfbos.org\"/>\n* he implemented programs within his district to calm traffic in conjunction with street beautification projects.<ref name=\"sfbos.org\"/>\n* his \u201cBlueprint for Homeless Reform Policy\u201d, introduced in 2001, was the product of a 15-year personal study which encompassed a 7-point package of ordinances and resolutions which established quality of life and civility laws and mandated policy changes within the homeless industry.  Hall directly questioned the efficacy of then-Supervisor Gavin Newsom\u2019s \u201cCare-Not-Cash\u201d initiative.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hpn.asu.edu/archives/2002-January/005342.html}}</ref>\n* he implemented the Safely Surrendered Baby Law (Senate Bill 1368) for San Francisco and passed the Safe Haven for Newborns legislation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfbos.org/ftp/uploadedfiles/bdsupvrs/resolutions02/r0615-02.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Treasure Island tenure==\nHall served on the Board of Supervisors until August 2004,<ref>{{cite news|title=Board gives maverick Hall a fond farewell|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2004/08/20/WBGFF86G8P1.DTL|newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle | first=Rachel|last=Gordon|date=31 August 2010}}</ref> when Mayor Gavin Newsom asked Hall to assume the post of Executive Director of the Treasure Island Development Authority. Mayor Newsom publicly stated that his choice was due to Hall's record of accomplishments in the area of public facilities and special projects.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2004/08/01/BAGD68104S1.DTL | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | first=Rachel | last=Gordon | title=SAN FRANCISCO / Newsom confirms he wants Hall for job / 2 panels must OK supervisor to run Treasure Island | date=2 September 2010}}</ref> Newsom appointed [[Sean Elsbernd]] to replace Hall on the Board of Supervisors.\n\nHall conducted on-going meetings with the developer regarding plans and contract compliance issues, as well as parallel interaction with the United States Navy principals responsible for re-conveyance of the property to San Francisco. The Navy had become skeptical of San Francisco's sincerity and the ability of the developer to issue a concrete redevelopment plan after more than seven years. Newsom insisted upon a renewal of the developer's contract, despite the fact that the developer had not met its terms; there were substantial payment shortfalls for specific developmental milestones, and a series of discarded timetable extensions. Newsom also insisted that other \u201cpartners\u201d be allowed to join the development team without going through the public bidding process as mandated by the City Charter.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2005/09/27/BAG4OEUHMT1.DTL | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | first=Charlie | last=Goodyear | title=SAN FRANCISCO / Treasure Island chief decries development delay | date=29 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2005, the Treasure Island Development Authority voted to require the resignation of Tony Hall from the project \u201cwithout cause.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fogcityjournal.com/news_in_brief/hall_fired_051012.shtml}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2005-10-13/bay-area/17395876_1_island-s-board-treasure-island-development-authority-city-hall | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | first=Cecilia M. | last=Vega | title=SAN FRANCISCO / Treasure Island chief may lose job in vote set today / Newsom speaks to board of directors about his concerns | date=13 October 2005}}</ref> Hall subsequently warned of the dangers of development on Treasure Island, calling it a \u201cseismically unsafe toxic landfill\u201d on top of the San Andreas fault.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/22/us/22bcintel.html?_r=2 | work=The New York Times | first=Hank | last=Pellissier | title=Local Intelligence \u2013 Building 1 | date=21 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nSince departing Treasure Island, Hall has maintained a blog on issues related to civic life in San Francisco, and is a columnist for the Westside Observer.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tonyhallsf.wordpress.com/}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Hall began a campaign for San Francisco mayor to challenge Newsom, but dropped out.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ebar.com/news/article.php?sec=news&article=2114}}</ref> In March 2011, Hall announced he was running for mayor a second time,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfexaminer.com/blogs/under-dome/2010/12/tony-hall-tweets-his-intent-run-mayor}}</ref> but his bid was unsuccessful.\n\n==Background and personal life==\nBorn in Los Angeles, Hall attended Loyola High School and graduated from UCLA with a degree in economics and public administration. He moved to San Francisco in 1964.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2001-02-06/news/17585618_1_irish-american-wedding-singer-political-appointees | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | first=Ilene | last=Lelchuk | title=Gonzalez calls the mayor a liar / Brown denies he said candidate is a racist | date=6 February 2001}}</ref> His volunteer and civic activities have included singing Mass at St. Brendan's Church on Sundays,<ref name=\"Lelchuk\"/> volunteering as a track coach at St. Ignatius Prep School,<ref name=\"Lelchuk\"/> and announcing the San Francisco\u2019s St. Patrick's Day Parade.<ref name=\"Lelchuk\"/>\n\nHall and his band \u201cThe Hallmarks\u201d perform at weddings and are a mainstay of the San Francisco music scene.<ref name=\"Lelchuk\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.tonyhallsf.com/ Campaign website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off|us}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Members of the San Francisco Board of Supervisors|Member of the San Francisco Board of Supervisors<br>District 7]] | before=District Created | after=[[Sean Elsbernd]] | years=2000&ndash;2004}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hall, Tony}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:San Francisco Board of Supervisors members]]\n[[Category:University of California, Los Angeles alumni]]\n", "name_user": "BriefEdits", "label": "safe", "comment": "Formatting. Added infobox.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tony_Hall_(supervisor)"}
{"title_page": "The Dumping Ground (series 8)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox television season\n| season_number        = 8\n| bgcolour             = #BCD4E6 \n| image                = \n| caption              = \n| country              = United Kingdom\n| network              = [[CBBC]]<br />[[CBBC HD]]\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2020|1|10|df=y}} \u2013 present\n| last_aired           = \n| num_episodes         = 24\n| episode_list         = List of The Dumping Ground episodes\n}}\n\nThe '''eight series''' of the British children's television series ''[[The Dumping Ground]]'' began broadcasting on 10 January 2020 on [[CBBC (TV channel)|CBBC]].<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/schedules/p00fzl9r/2020/01/10</ref> The series follows the lives of the children living in the fictional children's care home of Ashdene Ridge, nicknamed by them \"The Dumping Ground\". It is set to consist of twenty-four, thirty-minute episodes. It is the 16th series in [[The Story of Tracy Beaker franchise]].\n\n==Cast==\n{{Further|List of The Story of Tracy Beaker (franchise) characters}}\n\n===Main===\n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n*Miles Butler-Hughton as [[Tyler Lewis (Tracy Beaker Returns character)|Tyler Lewis]] (until episode 12)\n*[[Kia Pegg]] as [[Jody Jackson (Tracy Beaker Returns character)|Jody Jackson]]\n*Sarah Rayson as [[Floss Guppy]]\n* Stacy Liu as [[May-Li Wang]]\n*[[Ruben Reuter]] as [[Finn McLaine]]\n*[[Annabelle Davis]] as [[Sasha Bellman]]\n*[[Hannah Moncur]] as [[Chloe Reeves]]\n*Carma Hylton as [[Candi-Rose]] \n*Jasmine Uson as [[Taz De Souza]] \n*Leo James as [[Bird Wallis]]\n*Cole Wealleans-Watts as [[Jay Wallis]]\n*Josh Sangha as [[Sid Newton]]\n*Ava Potter as [[List of The Dumping Ground characters#Bec Hyde|Bec Hyde]]\n*Anya Cooke as Katy White\n*Louis Payne as Scott Jenson<ref>https://www.spotlight.com/interactive/cv/1/M143550.html</ref>\n*Chloe Lea as Viv (from episode 5)\n*Tut Nyuot as Nazeer (from episode 11)\n}}\n\n===Guest===\n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n*[[Gary Webster (actor)|Gary Webster]] as Al Winters<ref>https://twitter.com/RealGaryWebster/status/1213249495753998336</ref>\n*Steven Blakeley as Ed Grayson  \n*Endy McKay as Jenny Holmes \n*Cherry Campbell as Iona\n*Scott Karim as K'Alias\n*Lucy Thackeray as Stef\n*Matilda Shapland as Emma\n*Bethany Asher as Ivy\n*Geoff Berrisford as Jake\n*Omar Malik as Kamal Hameed\n*Connor Lawson as [[List of The Dumping Ground characters#Alex Walker|Alex Walker]]\n*Carlos Mapano as Jerome De Souza\n*Vanessa Hehir as Amanda\n*Solomon Israel as Ray\n*[[Jessica Revell]] as [[Elektra Perkins]]\n}}\n\n==Episodes==\nThe series' second half's directors include Hildegard Ryan (4 episodes),<ref>http://www.rochellestevens.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Credits-Ryan.pdf</ref> John Howlett, Vicki Kisner,<ref>https://uk.linkedin.com/in/nichol-hoye-6952179a</ref> and Gary Williams (4 episodes),<ref>http://www.greenbeetle.co.uk/offline-editor.html</ref> and produced by Emma Bodger.<ref>https://www.gemsagency.co.uk/cv_profile/hayley-boyd/1010</ref> Writers include Zoe Lister.<ref>http://nickturnermanagement.com/zoe-lister/</ref>\n\n<!--Sources are needed for all episode names, summaries are not written until the episode airs.-->\n<onlyinclude>{{Episode table |background= #BCD4E6 |overall=6 |series=6 |title=30 |director=14 |writer=20 |airdate=15 |viewers=10 |country=UK |viewersR=<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barb.co.uk/viewing-data/weekly-top-10/|title=Weekly Top 10 Programmes|publisher=[[Broadcasters' Audience Research Board]]|accessdate=7 January 2017}}</ref>|episodes=\n{{Episode table/part|p=1|c=#BCD4E6}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Dumping Ground (series 8)\n|EpisodeNumber   = 139\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n|Title           = Natural Selection\n|RTitle          =\n|DirectedBy      = Nicole Volavka\n|WrittenBy       = Julie Dixon\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|1|10|df=y}} \n|Viewers         = 0.15\n|ShortSummary    = With Mike gone, the day arrives for a new head care worker to be appointed. May-Li is hoping to be promoted, so to make sure she is, Jody makes sure the kids don't step out of line so she gets the job. However, Floss sees that May-Li is basing her case study presentation on Jody including everything she's been through and even her personal information. When she learns about this, Jody is furious and rebels against May-Li, stopping her from giving her presentation and forcing her to resign. Another man, Al, becomes head care worker instead. This makes everyone else hate Jody but Jody ignores them.\n\n'''First Appearance''': Louis Payne as [[List of The Dumping Ground characters#Scott Jenson|Scott Jenson]]\n|LineColor \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 = #BCD4E6\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Dumping Ground (series 8)\n|EpisodeNumber   = 140\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n|Title           = Follow My Leader\n|RTitle          =\n|DirectedBy      = Nicole Volavka\n|WrittenBy       = Dawn Harrison\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|1|17|df=y}} \n|Viewers         = 0.15\n|ShortSummary    = Under Al's leadership, the DG has dissolved into chaos despite the efforts of the temporary assistant care worker, Scott. Al is proving to be unprofessional, as well as biased against certain kids, leaving Tyler unhappy along with many of the others. When May-Li briefly returns to return her keys, Taz and Katy stow away in her car and find her working at a nursery. Believing she has found a new job, they try to sabotage her position, only to learn that she is doing her regular shift at Henry's nursery. Despite their hopes she will return, May-Li tells them she has been applying for other positions and is going to an interview later that day. Meanwhile, Tyler hatches a plan to persuade Al to quit by handing him several folders of false paperwork to fill in, but Jody, who remains unrepentant over her actions, ruins the plan. Sasha and Chloe attempt to find out more about whether they can trust Scott. Sid learns about May-Li's interview and decides to go looking for her alone. When the others find out he is missing, Tyler berates Jody for her lack of remorse, leading her to help in the efforts to find him. They find him with the help of May-Li and discover he's sprained his ankle. After taking him to hospital Jody apologises to May-Li but learns that she has been offered the new job. Before she can accept it, however, Al admits he is not suitable for a head care worker role and relinquishes his position to her with an admission that she was the best candidate. With May-Li appointed as head care worker, and Scott appointed as a permanent care worker at Ashdene Ridge, everyone is delighted to see that the DG is officially back in business.\n|LineColor       = #BCD4E6\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Dumping Ground (series 8)\n|EpisodeNumber   = 141\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 3\n|Title           = Auld Lang Syne\n|RTitle          =\n|DirectedBy      = Nicole Volavka \n|WrittenBy       = Claire Miller\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|1|24|df=y}} \n|Viewers         = 0.17\n|ShortSummary    = It's [[burns day]] at the DG and Chloe is excited as her old friend from [[Scotland]] is visiting for the occasion but the reunion ends up reminding her painfully about her mother. Meanwhile, Bec is depressed on Burns Day as it's also the anniversary of her mothers death. She tries to keep it a secret but Taz finds out and ends up telling everyone else, making Bec angry. Meanwhile, Tyler and Sid go against Jody and Katy in the dance competition for burns day which turns to war.\n|LineColor       = #BCD4E6\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Dumping Ground (series 8)\n|EpisodeNumber   = 142\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 4\n|Title           = Somebody\n|RTitle          =\n|DirectedBy      = Nicole Volavka\n|WrittenBy       = Rachel Smith\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|1|31|df=y}} \n|Viewers         = 0.15\n|ShortSummary    = While on a tour with a well known street artist, Sasha discovers that his latest piece is almost identical to a piece she has made for her college exhibition. Convinced the artist, K'Alias, has stolen her idea, she enlists Tyler and Jody's help to try and prove it. While on another tour of his studio, she discovers a picture of him in front of her work, solidifying her suspicions. After angrily confronting him, during which he claims to not even remember any of her work, she storms out. Now convinced she has wasted her life trying to be an artist, Sasha proceeds to vandalise K'Alias' piece. Elsewhere, Candi-Rose decides to take up vlogging, wanting to try and gain large numbers of followers. She is dismayed to learn that her own efforts are attracting little attention and most of her followers are down to Finn and Sid making their own vlog on hers. Finn assures her that she doesn't need the attention of anonymous people online as she is already liked by everyone in the house, cheering her up greatly. Meanwhile, Floss has a row with Scott about an upcoming trip and writes an angry note saying he should be sacked in retaliation. After hearing him talk about her more leniently she regrets it and tries to get the note back, only to learn that he had already seen it. Sasha gets a visit from K'Alias, who assures her that it can be difficult to find someone has already thought of your idea, but that she shouldn't give up her dream because one piece didn't work out. He offers to be her mentor, and Sasha accepts. Together the pair properly unveil K'Alias' piece, with Sasha's sprayed additions still in place.\n\n'''Absent''': Ava Potter as Bec Hyde\n|LineColor       = #BCD4E6\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Dumping Ground (series 8)\n|EpisodeNumber   = 143\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 5\n|Title           = Sugar and Spice\n|RTitle          =\n|DirectedBy      = Sean Glynn\n|WrittenBy       = Christine Robertson\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|7|df=y}} \n|Viewers         = 0.14\n|ShortSummary    = Floss meets a dream family who want to foster her. The Mum and sister in the family seem perfect so Floss looks at her weaknesses to try and become the perfect daughter but it doesn't go to plan. Meanwhile, new girl Viv arrives and she and Sasha get competitive on a challenge about general knowledge on the other young people and both soon become enemies whist Scott and Jay become competitive in yoga.\n\n'''First Appearance''': Chloe Lea as Viv\n'''Absent''': Ava Potter as Bec Hyde\n|LineColor       = #BCD4E6\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Dumping Ground (series 8)\n|EpisodeNumber   = 144\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 6\n|Title           = Love Hearts And Roses\n|RTitle          =\n|DirectedBy      = Sean Glynn\n|WrittenBy       = John Hickman\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|14|df=y}}\n|Viewers         = 0.17\n|ShortSummary    = It's [[Valentines Day]] at the DG and Finn tries to get the perfect date with Ivy whilst Tyler tries too hard to make the day perfect for him and Jody. Meanwhile, Chloe is not pleased to be going gaming with Jake for their Valentine's day treat and tries to get them to break up in revenge.\n|LineColor       = #BCD4E6\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Dumping Ground (series 8)\n|EpisodeNumber   = 145\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 7\n|Title           = A Matter of Life and Debt\n|RTitle          =\n|DirectedBy      = Sean Glynn\n|WrittenBy       = Anthony MacMurray\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|21|df=y}}\n|Viewers         = 0.16\n|ShortSummary    = Tyler discovers from his step-dad that his real Dad has passed, away. He doesn't care at first as his Dad left Tyler and his Mum when Tyler was just a baby but later learns that his father came back and lived nearby. Tyler and his step-dad explore his Dad's flat and learn more about him and Tyler finally starts to feel the impact on him because of his Dad's death and discovers that he needs help from family and friends to get through life. Meanwhile, Sasha notices how some of the YP need money as their allowances have run out and as Sasha has spare, they start asking for loans and Sasha and Jay eventually start off their loan bank. However, Sasha uses almost all her money on loans and can't afford to buy tickets for a concert she wants to go to and soon finds herself begging for loans. Taz discovers her Dad was unable to pay for his electricity bills and uses her talent for playing the piano to raise money for him so he can afford the bills.\n\n'''Absent''': Chloe Lea as Viv and Ava Potter as Bec Hyde\n\n|LineColor       = #BCD4E6\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Dumping Ground (series 8)\n|EpisodeNumber   = 146\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 8\n|Title           = Risk\n|RTitle          =\n|DirectedBy      = Sean Glynn \n|WrittenBy       = Gareth Sergeant\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|28|df=y}}\n|Viewers         = 0.19\n|ShortSummary    = Tired of being considered a \"goody two shoes\", Chloe decides to become a \"fixer\" in the DG, forcing her to take huge risks to get the other kids out of trouble. Meanwhile, after spending the day with Alex, Finn decides that he wants to live with him but soon realises that it isn't as simple as it seems. Elsewhere Sid's ventriloquist dummy is taken and held to ransom, forcing him to provide different treats to get him back.\n\n'''Guest Appearance''': Connor Lawson as [[List of The Dumping Ground characters#Alex Walker|Alex Walker]]\n\n'''Absent''': Chloe Lea as Viv\n|LineColor       = #BCD4E6\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Dumping Ground (series 8)\n|EpisodeNumber   = 147\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 9\n|Title           = The Replacement\n|RTitle          =\n|DirectedBy      = Alex Jacob\n|WrittenBy       = Hannah George\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|06|df=y}}\n|Viewers         = <0.13\n|ShortSummary    = Taz learns that her dad has a new girlfriend and refuses to accept it, thinking that she is making him forget about her mum. Meanwhile, Candi-Rose bribes Jay with a ticket to a trainer launch to be her servant for the day, while Sasha tries to help Finn overcome his fear of spiders.\n|LineColor       = #BCD4E6\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Dumping Ground (series 8)\n|EpisodeNumber   = 148\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 10\n|Title           = Do the Right Thing\n|RTitle          =\n|DirectedBy      = Alex Jacob\n|WrittenBy       = Suzanne Cowie\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|13|df=y}}\n|Viewers         = 0.11\n|ShortSummary    = Viv departs from the Dumping Ground to go and live with her uncle Ray who used to steal things but now claims to have changed. However, Viv discovers that he's lost his job and is now stealing and selling phones to afford the rent. Hurt that her uncle hasn't really changed, Viv returns to Ashdene Ridge. Meanwhile, Bec discovers a stray dog and tries to keep it a secret from May-Li and Scott, and Bird tries to help numerous Ashdene Ridge residents with numerous things but messes it up.\n|LineColor       = #BCD4E6\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Dumping Ground (series 8)\n|EpisodeNumber   = 149\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 11\n|Title           = Trouble in Paradise\n|RTitle          =\n|DirectedBy      = Alex Jacob\n|WrittenBy       = Claire Miller\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|20|df=y}}\n|Viewers         = 0.16\n|ShortSummary    = Tyler is offered the chance to go to [[St. Lucia]] to live with his Mum but because of the ongoing relationship between him and Jody, he can't risk leaving Jody behind. Sid observes them kissing and when word gets to May-Li and Scott about this, they make life harder for Jody and Tyler - separating them in order to keep them both at the DG. Meanwhile, Jay tries to prove to new boy Nazeer that he practically owns the DG.\n\n'''First Appearance''': Tut Nuyot as Nazeer\n \n|LineColor       = #BCD4E6\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Dumping Ground (series 8)\n|EpisodeNumber   = 150\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 12\n|Title           = Go Your Own Way\n|RTitle          =\n|DirectedBy      = Alex Jacob\n|WrittenBy       = Mark Stevenson\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|27|df=y}}\n|Viewers         = 0.13\n|ShortSummary    = Tyle