[[1984 Indianapolis 500|1984]]<small> with:</small><br />[[Roberto Guerrero]] | before = [[Teo Fabi]] | after = [[Arie Luyendyk]]}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Marlboro Challenge]]<br>winner |before=[[Bobby Rahal]]|after= [[Al Unser, Jr.]]|years=1988}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Marlboro Challenge]]<br>winner |before=[[Rick Mears]]|after= [[Emerson Fittipaldi]]|years=1991}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Champ Car|CART Series]]<br>[[Champion]] |before=[[Al Unser, Jr.]]|after= [[Bobby Rahal]]|years=[[1991 IndyCar season|1991]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{AndrettiGreenRacing}}\n{{CART/CCWS Drivers' Champions}}\n{{American open-wheel car racing champions}}\n{{Andretti family}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Andretti, Michael}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Bethlehem, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Racing drivers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Indianapolis 500 drivers]]\n[[Category:Indianapolis 500 Rookies of the Year]]\n[[Category:American Formula One drivers]]\n[[Category:McLaren Formula One drivers]]\n[[Category:Champ Car champions]]\n[[Category:Champ Car drivers]]\n[[Category:IndyCar Series drivers]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Championship drivers]]\n[[Category:International Race of Champions drivers]]\n[[Category:World Touring Car Championship drivers]]\n[[Category:SCCA Formula Super Vee drivers]]\n[[Category:IndyCar Series team owners]]\n[[Category:Formula E team owners]]\n[[Category:24 Hours of Le Mans drivers]]\n[[Category:24 Hours of Daytona drivers]]\n[[Category:12 Hours of Sebring drivers]]\n[[Category:World Sportscar Championship drivers]]\n[[Category:IMSA GT Championship drivers]]\n[[Category:A1 Grand Prix team owners]]\n[[Category:Nazareth Area High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Andretti family]]\n[[Category:20th-century American racing drivers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American racing drivers]]\n[[Category:SCCA National Championship Runoffs participants]]\n[[Category:Trans-Am Series drivers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox racing driver <!-- See Template:Infobox racing driver for more information -->\n| name              = Michael Andretti\n| image             = Michael Andretti 2007 Michigan.jpg\n| imagesize         =\n| caption           = Andretti at Michigan in 2007\n| nationality       = {{flagicon|USA}} American\n| birth_name        = Michael Mario Andretti\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1962|10|5}}\n| birth_place       = [[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| related to        = [[Mario Andretti]] (father)<br/>[[Jeff Andretti]] (brother)<br/>[[Marco Andretti]] (son)<br/>[[Aldo Andretti]] (uncle)<br/>[[John Andretti]] (cousin)<br/>[[Adam Andretti]] (cousin)\n| current series    = [[Champ Car|CART]]\n| first year        = [[1983 IndyCar season|1983]]\n| current team      = [[Andretti Autosport]]\n| car number        =\n| former teams      = [[Kraco Enterprises|Kraco Racing]]<br/>[[Newman/Haas Racing]]<br/>[[Chip Ganassi Racing|Target Chip Ganassi Racing]]<br/>[[Andretti Autosport|Team Motorola]]\n| starts            = 317\n| wins              = 42\n| poles             = 32\n| fastest laps      =\n| best finish       = 1st\n| year              = [[1991 IndyCar season|1991]]\n| prev series       = [[Champ Car|CART IndyCar World Series]]<br/>[[Formula One]]<br/>[[Champ Car|CART IndyCar World Series]]\n| prev series years = 1983-1992<br/>1993<br/>1994-2002\n| titles            = 1\n| title years       = 1991\n| awards            = CART IndyCar World Series Champion\n| award years       = 1991\n| module            =\n{{Infobox F1 driver|embed=yes\n| nationality = {{flagicon|USA}} American\n| birth_date = \n| Years = {{F1|1993}}\n| Team(s) = [[McLaren (racing)|McLaren]]\n| Races = 13\n| Championships = 0\n| Wins = 0\n| Podiums = 1\n| Points = 7\n| Poles = 0\n| Fastest laps = 0\n| First race = [[1993 South African Grand Prix]]\n| First win = \n| Last win = \n| Last race = [[1993 Italian Grand Prix]]\n}}\n}}\n'''Michael Mario Andretti''' (born October 5, 1962) is an American former auto racing driver and current team owner.  Statistically one of the most successful drivers in the history of [[American open-wheel car racing]], Andretti won the [[1991 CART PPG Indy Car World Series]] and amassed 42 race victories, the most in the CART era and fourth-most all time.<ref name=\"CCSATR\">{{cite web|url=http://www.champcarstats.com/records/records-career.htm|title=All-Time Records - Career|work=champcarstats.com|accessdate=3 April 2018}}</ref>  Since his retirement from active racing, Andretti has owned [[Andretti Autosport]], which has won four IndyCar Series championships and five [[Indianapolis 500]] races.\n\nHe is the son of [[List of Formula One World Drivers' Champions|Formula One World Champion]] and Indianapolis 500 winner [[Mario Andretti]], and the father of current IndyCar Series driver [[Marco Andretti]].\n\n==Racing career==\n\n===Early career===\n\nMichael Andretti was born to Dee Ann and racing legend [[Mario Andretti]], a race car driver who became a four-time IndyCar champion and the 1978 Formula One World Champion.\n\nFollowing a successful career racing karts, winning 50 of his 75 races over eight years, Michael moved into racing cars. He obtained his [[Sports Car Club of America|SCCA]] National License in 1980, then won six races to claim the SCCA's Northeast Division Formula Ford championship in 1981. He also drove in a number of [[Formula Vee]] races in regional SCCA events. In 1982, he won six of the 11 races on his way to winning the [[Super Vee|Robert Bosch US Formula Super Vee Championship]]. He also won the opening race of the 1983 Super Vee season before he moved up to drive in [[Formula Atlantic]], and won his second title by winning the [[Formula Mondial|FIA Formula Mondial North American Cup]] the following season. Although he made his international sports car debut at the [[1982 24 Hours of Le Mans]], he was denied the opportunity to race, as the Mirage M12 he had chosen to race with his father was disqualified 80 minutes before the race was due to start. The father and son partnership returned to the [[Circuit de la Sarthe]] the following year, and were joined by [[Philippe Alliot]] in the [[Kremer Racing|Porsche Kremer Racing]]'s [[Porsche 956]], taking third place. Michael also raced alongside his father in the Riverside 6 Hours where they were joined by [[A. J. Foyt]] and [[Preston Henn]], but the [[Porsche 935]] failed to finish. The father and son duo paired up again the [[1984 24 Hours of Daytona|1984 Daytona 24 Hours]], this time in a full-works [[Porsche 962]], which made its race debut. They took pole position, but during the race, the engine broke.<ref name=\"teamdan.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.teamdan.com/archive/www2/superv/82svrob.html|title=1982 Robert Bosch US Formula Super Vee Championship|work=teamdan.com|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"champcarstats.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.champcarstats.com/atlantic/year/1983.htm|title=1983 FIA Formula Mondial North American Cup|work=champcarstats.com|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.texacohavoline42.com/media/history/cart/michael_andretti.asp |accessdate=December 20, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061231010720/http://www.texacohavoline42.com/media/history/cart/michael_andretti.asp |archivedate=December 31, 2006 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.racingsportscars.com/driver/results/Michael-Andretti-USA.html|title=Michael Andretti (USA) - All Results|publisher=Racing Sports Cars|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.racingsportscars.com/photo/Le_Mans-1982-06-20.html|title=Le Mans 24 Hours|publisher=Racing Sports Cars|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.racingsportscars.com/photo/Le_Mans-1983-06-19-photo.html|title=Le Mans 24 Hours|publisher=Racing Sports Cars|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Cotton\">Martin Cotton, \"Directory of World Sportscars GROUP C and IMSA Cars from 1982\" (Aston Publications, {{ISBN|0-946627-38-X}}, 1988)</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.racingsportscars.com/photo/Riverside-1983-04-24.html|title=Riverside 6 Hours|publisher=Racing Sports Cars|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===CART===\n[[File:1986 March 86C Indy Car.JPG|right|thumb|Andretti's first race winning Indy Car, now at [[National Motor Museum, Beaulieu]], England.]]\nHe made his [[Champ Car|CART]] debut in [[1983 CART PPG Indy Car World Series|1983]], racing for the [[Kraco Enterprises]] team. Andretti re-signed for Kraco to undertake the 1984 season, where he managed five third-place finishes and ended his rookie season in seventh overall. In the [[1984 Indianapolis 500|Indianapolis 500]], he finished fifth and shared the [[List of Indianapolis 500 Rookies of the Year|Rookie of the Year]] award with [[Roberto Guerrero]]. He went on to win his first [[American Championship Car Racing|IndyCar]] race in [[1986 IndyCar season|1986]] in the [[Grand Prix of Long Beach|Toyota Grand Prix of Long Beach]]. The season became a two-man battle for the championship title, between Michael and [[Bobby Rahal]]. Andretti would take the points lead with his victory on the [[Milwaukee Mile]]. A week later, on [[Father's Day (United States)|Father's Day]], Michael was leading on the final lap at [[Portland International Raceway|Portland]], when his [[March Engineering|March-Cosworth 86C]] ran out of fuel, allowing his father, Mario, to beat him by just 0.07 seconds. It was one of the most shocking finishes in the history of IndyCar, and the closest finish (until 1997). With Rahal continuing to win races, Andretti's consistent finishing only allowed Rahal a nine-point lead in the standing with two races remaining. Andretti won a key victory in at [[Phoenix International Raceway|Phoenix]]. Going into the season finale at [[Tamiami Park]], Andretti was just three points behind Rahal, but neither driver were a factor in the race, with Andretti retiring with a broken halfshaft.<ref name=\"niashf.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.niashf.org/inductees/michael-andretti/|title=Michael Andretti|work=National Italian American Sports Hall of Fame|accessdate=January 26, 2016|date=2012-11-07}}</ref><ref name=\"racing-reference.info\">{{cite web|url=http://www.racing-reference.info/driver/Michael_Andretti|title=Michael Andretti Career Statistics|publisher=Racing Reference|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.champcarstats.com/drivers/AndrettiMichael.htm|title=Michael Andretti|work=champcarstats.com|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn a one-off race with [[Alfa Corse]], he took part in the inaugural World Touring Car race, [[1987 Monza 500|500 km di Monza]]. Paired with [[Alessandro Nannini]], they finished 16th overall, second in class. Back in CART, he continued with Kraco in 1987, and like 1986, the championship was between Andretti and Rahal. Michael would win the [[Firestone Indy 400|Michigan 500]], drawing within nine points of Rahal.  With him winning in dominating fashion at [[Nazareth Speedway]], his championship hopes remained alive, although Rahal clinched the championship at the next race. Andretti would also win the season finale, [[Tamiami Park]]. He would finish runner-up for the second season in a row. Back in June 1987, Michael joined Hendrick Motorsport to race a [[Chevrolet Corvette GTP]] in the Mid-Ohio 500&nbsp;km, this time joined by his cousin, [[John Andretti]], where they finished 11th.<ref name=\"niashf.org\"/><ref name=\"racing-reference.info\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.touringcarracing.net/Races/1987%20Monza.html|title=1987 WTC - round 1|work=touringcarracing.net|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.racingsportscars.com/photo/Mid-Ohio-1987-06-07.html|title=Mid-Ohio 500 Kilometres|publisher=Racing Sports Cars|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:962 Andrettis.jpg|right|thumb|Andretti's family 962C, Le Mans 1988]]\n[[File:1989Porsche962MarioAndrettiMichaelAndrettiMillerHighLife.jpg|thumb|right|Michael and Mario's 1989 [[Porsche 962]] driven in the [[24 Hours of Daytona]].]]\n\nFollowing Porsche's defeat in the [[1988 24 Hours of Daytona|1988 Daytona 24 Hours]], Porsche entered a [[Porsche 962|962C]] at [[1988 24 Hours of Le Mans|Le Mans]] for Mario, Michael and John. They were tremendously competitive in the first half of the race, until the Andretti family's car needed minor repairs before lapsing on to five cylinders, finishing sixth overall. Michael and Mario join Busby Racing for [[1989 24 Hours of Daytona|1989 Daytona 24 Hours]], only for their 962 to retire with brakes problems.<ref name=\"Cotton\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.racingsportscars.com/photo/Daytona-1989-02-05.html|title=Daytona 24 Hours|publisher=Racing Sports Cars|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe 1988 CART season was a lean year for Michael. He remained with Kraco, scoring a just one race win, in the non-champion [[Marlboro Challenge]].\n\n1989 saw a change of teams, which Michael switching to [[Newman/Haas Racing]], to partner, a certain Mario Andretti. Winning two races during the season, [[Honda Indy Toronto|Molson Indy Toronto]] and [[Firestone Indy 400|Marlboro 500]] at the [[Michigan International Speedway]], on his way to third in the standing. For 1990, [[Al Unser, Jr.]] would become champion, Andretti was his nearest competitor, winning five races and four poles. In the second-to-last race of the season at Nazareth, Unser crashed out, giving Andretti a huge opportunity to close the gap. Andretti managed only a sixth-place finish, and could not capitalize on Unser's misfortune. Unser left Nazareth with a 27-point lead, enough to clinch the championship. Andretti would finish runner-up once again.<ref name=\"racing-reference.info\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nFor the 1991 Daytona 24, Mario was joined by both his sons this time, with Michael being joined by [[Jeff Andretti]]. Piloting a [[Dauer Sportwagen|Jochen Dauer Racing]] entered Porsche 962, they were classified fifth overall, despite not finishing the race.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.racingsportscars.com/photo/Daytona-1991-02-03.html|title=Daytona 24 Hours|publisher=Racing Sports Cars|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:MichaelAndretti.jpg|right|thumb|Andretti racing at [[Monterey, California]], October 1991]]\nAndretti achieved major title success by winning the [[1991 CART PPG Indy Car World Series]] for Newman/Haas Racing. He won a total eight of 17 races, eight poles and led more than half of the laps during the season, but Rahal still took the championship battle down to the final race of the season. Andretti's season started slowly, recording [[Did Not Finish|DNFs]] in the opening two events, then the heartbreaking second place at the Indy 500. He recovered from this, winning four of the last five races of the season and with Rahal retiring during the title decider at [[Mazda Raceway Laguna Seca|Laguna Seca]], he cruised to the title. The day before, he won the non-championship, [[Marlboro Challenge]] for a second time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://racing-reference.info/raceyear/1991/R|title=CART Results for 1991 |publisher=Racing Reference|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nRemaining with Newman/Haas for 1992, Michael's season started slowly, but then wins three races out of four mid-season. Despite taking two more wins later in the year, including the season finale at Laguna Seca, Rahal beat him again to the title by just four points. He would leave for F1 at the end of the year, with his seat going to the reigning Formula One World Champion, [[Nigel Mansell]], who would win the 1993 CART title in his rookie season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://racing-reference.info/raceyear/1992/R|title=CART Results for 1992|publisher=Racing Reference|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFor four seasons between 1989 and 1992, Michael enjoyed the unique experience, privilege and honour of having his father as his teammate at Newman/Haas. Together, they established a number of first, including the first father-son front row, for the 1986 Dana 200 for Special Olympics at [[Phoenix International Raceway|Phoenix]], and the first of 15 father-son podiums in the 1984 Cribari Wines 300K at [[Mazda Raceway Laguna Seca|Laguna Seca]], with the last coming nearly a decade later in the [[1992 Daikyo IndyCar Grand Prix]], around the street of [[Surfers Paradise Street Circuit|Surfers Paradise]].<ref name=\"mshf.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mshf.com/hall-of-fame/inductees/michael-andretti.html|title=Andretti, Michael - Open Wheel - 2008|publisher=Motorsports Hall of Fame of America|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"islandconnections.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.islandconnections.com/edit/andretti.htm|title=Michael Andretti - Racing's Top Driver & Successful Entrepreneur|publisher=Island Connections|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Futility at Indianapolis===\n\nThe Andretti family's bad luck at the [[Indianapolis Motor Speedway]] is known as the [[Andretti Curse]]. He shared Rookie of the Year honours with Guerrero in 1984, when he finished fifth. However, in [[1991 Indianapolis 500|1991]], he led with 12 laps remaining, but finished second to [[Rick Mears]] after battling the multiple Indy 500 winner. The pair of them traded memorable late-lap outside passes for the lead in Turn One. The next year, [[1992 Indianapolis 500|1992]], he dominated the race, leading four-fifths of the laps, but, with 11 laps remaining after holding a two-lap lead, his fuel pump failed, and his car coasted to a stop. He was classified in 13th place. He also dropped out while leading the Indy 500 in [[1989 Indianapolis 500|1989]], [[1995 Indianapolis 500|1995]] and [[2003 Indianapolis 500|2003]]. Andretti holds the record for [[List of Indianapolis 500 lap leaders|most laps led]] in the Indy 500 without having achieved a victory.<ref name=\"mshf.com\"/>\n\n===Formula One===\nFor the 1993 season, Michael signed for [[McLaren|Marlboro McLaren]], to partner the triple World Drivers' Champion [[Ayrton Senna]] in their [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] HBD [[V8]] powered [[McLaren MP4/8|MP4/8]]. He signed during the summer of 1992 and the deal was announced at [[Autodromo Nazionale Monza|Monza]] over the weekend of the [[1992 Italian Grand Prix]].\n\n\"I think he can win Grands Prix and become the World Champion,\" said [[Ron Dennis]], McLaren's team principal. \"It's not a question of which country you come from. It's how you demonstrate your desire to win.\" There were practical factors that mitigated against Andretti being able to show competitive form in his debut season in F1. The rule changes introduced that season destroyed his hopes of unrestricted laps in free practice during which he could learn the tracks, as most were unfamiliar to him. From the start of 1993, just 23 laps were allowed in the morning's untimed session and only twelve in the qualifying session.<ref name=\"mclaren.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mclaren.com/formula1/heritage/driver/michael-andretti/|title=McLaren Formula 1 - Heritage - Michael Andretti|publisher=McLaren|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:Andretti 1993 European GP.jpg|thumb|left|Andretti driving for [[McLaren]] at the [[1993 European Grand Prix]]]]\nWith the pressure intensifying, Michael began the year with crashes in the [[Kyalami]] and at [[Aut\u00f3dromo Jos\u00e9 Carlos Pace|Interlagos]]. In the latter of these two, he had a massive collision at the start with Gerhard Berger in a Ferrari. He then qualified sixth for the [[1993 European Grand Prix|Sega European Grand Prix]] at [[Donington Park]], but he collided with [[Karl Wendlinger]]'s [[Sauber]] on the opening lap. Next time out at [[1993 San Marino Grand Prix|Imola]], he again fell foul of Wendlinger after a drive that might have ended with a visit to the podium, and many critics cited this as the key turning point for the American.<ref name=\"mclaren.com\"/><ref name=\"atlasf1.autosport.com\">{{cite web|url=http://atlasf1.autosport.com/2000/ita/okeefe.html|title=Man for One Season|publisher=Atlas F1|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[1993 Spanish Grand Prix|Gran Premio de Espa\u00f1a]], Andretti finally completed a race, finishing fifth amongst the established front runners.<ref name=\"atlasf1.autosport.com\"/> However, his showing was criticized by former McLaren World Champion [[James Hunt]] because Andretti was lapped by his teammate Senna.\n  \nHe would finish in the points on three occasions, but he could never quite string things together consistently. He never fully got to grips with the McLaren MP4/8. Highly technical aspects which he was not used to in the [[American Championship Car Racing#Comparison with Formula One|technologically simpler IndyCars]] such as [[active suspension]] and [[traction control system|traction control]] hampered Andretti's chances as did the standing starts used in F1. Some in the industry also felt that since he commuted to races and test sessions from the United States, rather than relocating full-time to Europe was also a contributing factor to his lack of success in Formula One. At the time, McLaren's Special Projects Manager, long-time Andretti family friend Tyler Alexander, who had been involved in F1 since the mid-1960s, had urged Michael to relocate to England as he knew times had changed from when Mario had raced to the 1978 World Championship. True enough, he finished third at Monza (which would prove to be his last Formula One race), but with three races remaining, he left the team and the championship by mutual agreement after the race.<ref name=\"mclaren.com\"/><ref name=\"atlasf1.autosport.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/09/08/sports/sports-people-auto-racing-andretti-switches-to-mclaren-team.html|title=Andretti Switches to McLaren Team|date=September 8, 1992|work=AP|via=The New York Times|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Michael's son [[Marco Andretti|Marco]], the McLaren team \"sabotaged\" his father's chances at being competitive in order to replace him with the team's test driver [[Mika H\u00e4kkinen]], who would require a smaller salary. \"The reality of it was, they had Mika H\u00e4kkinen ready to come in for a lot less than what my dad was getting paid, and that's all it was. Right then and there, they had to make him look [bad],\" claimed Marco in 2008. \"They would make the car do weird things in the corner electronically, stuff out of his control.\" However, Andretti still had problems in practice for the [[1993 Italian Grand Prix|Italian Grand Prix]], and both he and Senna spun off with brake balance problems early in the race. Andretti was able to continue and fought back up to third, holding off Wendlinger. Throughout the season, Senna experienced similar reliability problems to Andretti, mainly electronic gremlins, particularly in [[1993 San Marino Grand Prix|San Marino]], [[1993 Canadian Grand Prix|Canada]], [[1993 Hungarian Grand Prix|Hungary]] and [[1993 Belgian Grand Prix|Belgium]], although H\u00e4kkinen equalled Andretti's third place Monza finish in [[1993 Japanese Grand Prix|Japan]], while Senna won both the Japanese Grand Prix and the season ending [[1993 Australian Grand Prix|Australian Grand Prix]], his final race for McLaren.<ref name=\"mclaren.com\"/><ref name=\"atlasf1.autosport.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nwherald.com/articles/2008/05/22/sports/other_sports/doc4835195490406345041530.txt|title=Local News and Video for McHenry County, Illinois|work=Northwest Herald}}{{cbignore}}{{dead link|date=January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grandprix.com/gpe/rr546.html|title=Portuguese GP, 1993 Race Report - GP Encyclopedia - F1 History on Grandprix.com|publisher=Grandprix.com|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grandprix.com/gpe/rr548.html|title=Australian GP, 1993 Race Report - GP Encyclopedia - F1 History on Grandprix.com|publisher=Grandprix.com|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref> And according to H\u00e4kkinen in a much later interview, Andretti was commuting to Europe from the United States, and was not in Europe enough when testing needed to be done, allowing H\u00e4kkinen to consistently show his speed and build a relationship with the team. H\u00e4kkinen had also said that Andretti's mental approach was all wrong, and he did not realize the kind of incredible sacrifices one needed to make in order to succeed in Formula One.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x2j7huj|title=F1 Legends - Mika Hakkinen - Video Dailymotion|date=11 March 2015|website=Dailymotion|accessdate=15 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIt has also been reported that at the start of the 1993 season, Dennis signed H\u00e4kkinen as a backup to Senna, who was initially reluctant to commit to the team for the whole season (Senna's move to [[WilliamsF1|Williams]] had to wait until the next season because his rival [[Alain Prost]] was having his retirement season there and had it written into his contract that they could not sign the Brazilian triple World Champion as his teammate). This created a difficult atmosphere for Andretti, who would be in the shadow of the brilliant Brazilian, and also faced the threat of being replaced by H\u00e4kkinen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.f1rejects.com/centrale/andretti/index.html |title=Michael Andretti |publisher=F1 Rejects |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512065448/http://f1rejects.com/centrale/andretti/index.html |archivedate=May 12, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Return to CART===\n\nAndretti returned to the IndyCar racing after his unsuccessful season in Formula One with [[Chip Ganassi Racing|Target Chip Ganassi Racing]], where he once again proved very successful. He went on to win in his very first race back in the series at the [[1994 Australian FAI Indycar Grand Prix]], around the [[Surfers Paradise Street Circuit]] in [[Queensland]], [[Australia]], having led every lap along the way. That win also got [[Reynard Motorsport|Reynard]]'s first win in CART in their debut. Although the season may not have gone the way Michael would have liked, he did win again in the [[Honda Indy Toronto|Molson Indy Toronto]], taking a record fourth win. By the time he retired, Michael would have won seven times around the [[Exhibition Place]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://racing-reference.info/raceyear/1994/R|title=CART Results for 1994|publisher=Racing Reference|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn [[1995 PPG Indy Car World|1995]], he returned to [[Newman/Haas Racing]]. He had a consistent season, scoring points in every round, but taking just the one win, in Toronto, enable Andretti to claim fourth overall in the points standing. The following season, he would finish as runner-up to [[Jimmy Vasser]], in a season marred by the death of [[Jeff Krosnoff]] and split with [[IndyCar|Indy Racing League]], visiting victory lane on five occasions. Newman/Haas began a new relationship with [[Swift Engineering|Swift]] which did not prove to be very successful in 1997-1999. In 2000 the team used [[Lola Cars|Lola]] chassis and Michael won the [[Indy Japan 300|Firestone Firehawk 300]] held at [[Twin Ring Motegi]] in Japan, and again in Toronto.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://racing-reference.info/raceyear/1995/R|title=CART Results for 1995|publisher=Racing Reference|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://racing-reference.info/raceyear/1996/R|title=CART Results for 1996|publisher=Racing Reference|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"grandprix.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.grandprix.com/gpe/drv-andmic.html|title=Michael Andretti Profile - Drivers - GP Encyclopedia - F1 History on Grandprix.com|publisher=Grandprix.com|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nMichael tried again to win Le Mans in 1997, again alongside Mario, but joined on this occasion by [[Olivier Grouillard]]. Following an accident during the night, the trio were forced to retire their [[Courage Comp\u00e9tition|Courage C36]]. Michael would not return to la Sarthe as a driver.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.racingsportscars.com/photo/Le_Mans-1997-06-15.html|title=Le Mans 24 Hours|publisher=Racing Sports Cars|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFor 2001 he made the decision to move to Team Green as he wanted to try to win the Indianapolis 500 and Newman/Haas refused to enter the Indy Racing League event. Andretti ran in a third Team Green car with Motorola sponsorship and ran at Indianapolis. He led 16 laps, and was leading the race during a rain delay just beyond the halfway point. Had the race been halted due to the rain, he could have been declared the winner. The red flag, however, did not come out at the time and the race resumed. A punctured tyre, and a minor collision in the pits with eventual winner [[H\u00e9lio Castroneves]], driving for car owner [[Roger Penske]], slowed him down, and at the end of the day, Andretti settled for 3rd place. In July it was announced that Michael had bought the team and intended to shift the entire operation (which was renamed Andretti Green Racing) to the IRL.<ref name=\"grandprix.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://racing-reference.info/race/2001_Indianapolis_500/O|title=2001 Indianapolis 500|publisher=Racing Reference|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHis career in CART ended in [[2002 CART season|2002]], in which he took his 42nd and final career victory at the [[2002 Toyota Grand Prix of Long Beach|Toyota Grand Prix of Long Beach]] - placing him in third place for all-time victories in championship car racing behind his father, [[Mario Andretti]] (52 wins) and [[A. J. Foyt]] (67 wins).\n\nAndretti is also tied with [[Al Unser, Jr.]] for the most wins in a CART/IndyCar season with eight victories. He achieved this during his championship-winning season of [[1991 CART PPG Indy Car World Series|1991]]. Throughout his time in IndyCar, he retained a consistent and impressive record, finishing in the top ten of the championship on 17 occasions.<ref name=\"islandconnections.com\"/>\n\n==Semi-retirement and team owner==\n\nAfter competing in the [[2003 Indianapolis 500]], Andretti retired from full-time IndyCar racing. He led the race for 28 of the opening 94 laps before a throttle linkage failure put him out of contention once again. That year he bought into the \"Team Green\" squad run by brothers Kim and Barry Green in [[Champ Car|CART]]. It became [[Andretti Green Racing]] and for [[2003 IndyCar Series season|2003]], the team moved to the [[Indy Racing League]] [[IndyCar Series]].<ref name=\"grandprix.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/02/02/sports/plus-auto-racing-michael-andretti-to-retire-in-may.html|title=Michael Andretti To Retire in May|date=February 2, 2003|work=AP|via=The New York Times|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe team claimed consecutive IndyCar Series titles in [[2004 IndyCar Series season|2004]] and [[2005 IndyCar Series season|2005]], with [[Tony Kanaan]] and [[Dan Wheldon]] respectively, winning 11 of the 17 races, including the [[2005 Indianapolis 500|Indianapolis 500]]. The 2007 enhanced the Andretti legacy, when [[Dario Franchitti]] captured Andretti Green Racing its third Series title in four seasons, and its second [[2007 Indianapolis 500|Indianapolis 500]] win.<ref name=\"andrettiautosport.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.andrettiautosport.com/home.php?cid%3Dteam-profile-michael |accessdate=March 5, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150207034655/http://andrettiautosport.com/home.php?cid=team-profile-michael |archivedate=February 7, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:MichaelAndretti2007Indy500Practice.jpg|thumb|right|Andretti practicing for the 2007 Indy 500.]]\n\nAndretti returned to the driver's seat for the [[2006 Indianapolis 500]] in a one-time effort to assist the development of his son, [[Marco Andretti|Marco]], an IndyCar rookie for the [[2006 IndyCar Series season|'06 season]]. Michael led the race with four laps to go, before falling to second behind his son a lap later. He went on to finish third, while Marco only just missed out on the 500 victory after he was passed just before the start/finish line on the last lap by three-time IndyCar champion, [[Sam Hornish, Jr.]]\n\nAfter qualifying his car in 11th place for the [[2007 Indianapolis 500]], Andretti went on to finish 13th. He then announced that this would be his last Indy 500 as a driver. Andretti leaves driving competition at Indy with a frustrating distinction - the driver who's led the most laps (431) without winning the race. He competed in 16 Indy 500s, with a top finish of second in [[1991 Indianapolis 500|1991]], but led the race nine times.\n\nBy 2012, now racing under the name of [[Andretti Autosport]], they brought the [[2012 IndyCar Series season|2012 IndyCar Series]] championship back home. Michael served not only as the team owners, but as the strategist on [[Ryan Hunter-Reay]]'s four race victories. Hunter-Reay also captured the [[2014 Indianapolis 500]], with a close victory over [[H\u00e9lio Castroneves]].<ref name=\"andrettiautosport.com\"/>\n\nAt the beginning of 2018 he partnered with [[Ryan Walkinshaw's]] Walkinshaw Racing and [[Zak Brown]]'s [[United Autosports]] to create [[Walkinshaw Andretti United]] which competes in the [[Virgin Australia Supercars Championship]]\n\n==Other activities==\n\nIn 1996, Andretti invested in a Toyota dealership in his home state of Pennsylvania.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.mcall.com/1996-06-12/business/3087456_1_andretti-airport-toyota-greatest-race-car-driver-denny-clements|title=Andrettis Buy Toyota Dealership|work=tribunedigital-mcall|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAmong his personal appearances, Andretti appeared as a contestant on [[The Celebrity Apprentice 5|season 5]] of the reality TV series ''[[The Celebrity Apprentice]]'', which debuted in February 2012. Andretti joined the show as a last-minute replacement for his son Marco, who dropped out when Marco's friend [[Dan Wheldon]] was killed in the [[2011 IZOD IndyCar World Championship]] hours before ''Apprentice'' filming was scheduled to begin.  Andretti was fired in the fourth episode, after a presentation for Buick executives of the [[Buick Verano]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/03/12/michael-andretti-celebrity-apprentice_n_1340354.html|title='Celebrity Apprentice': Michael Andretti Reflects On Getting Fired (VIDEO)|date=12 March 2012|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref><ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/tv/marco-andretti-has-no-regrets-about-pulling-out-of-nbcs-celebrity-apprentice/2012/03/09/gIQAVBgV1R_story.html{{dead link|date=January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2012, Andretti Sports Marketing took over as promoter of the Milwaukee Mile IndyCar race. The company also promotes the [[Indy Grand Prix of Louisiana]], the [[Grand Prix of Miami (Indycar)|Miami ePrix]] and the [[Global RallyCross Championship]] events at [[RFK Stadium|Washington]] and [[Nassau Coliseum|New York]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/milwaukee/news/2012/03/19/andretti-firm-to-pay-25000-to-lease.html|title=Andretti firm to pay $25,000 to lease Milwaukee Mile|author=Mark Kass|date=March 19, 2012|work=Milwaukee Business Journal|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nAndretti attended [[Northampton Community College]] in Bethlehem, Pennsylvania. Andretti was married to Sandra \"Sandy\" Spinozzi from November 1985 to 1996 and they had two children, son [[Marco Andretti|Marco]] (born March 13, 1987) and daughter Marissa (born October 31, 1990). He remarried on December 24, 1997 to Leslie Wood. They had a son, Lucca, born September 16, 1999. Andretti officially separated from Leslie in 2003.  On September 7, 2004 Andretti filed for divorce. Two years later on July 15, 2006 Andretti announced his engagement to former [[Miss Oregon Teen USA]] 1994, [[Playboy Playmate of the Year]] 2000, model and actress [[Jodi Ann Paterson]]. The couple were married on October 7, 2006 at the Andretti Winery in Napa Valley, California. They have twin children, Mario and Miati (Mia), born February 13, 2014.\n\n==Andretti family==\n\n[[File:Michael Andretti at Carb Day 2015 at the Indianapolis 500 - Sarah Stierch 2.jpg|right|thumb|Andretti at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway in May 2015.]]\nMichael is from the famous Andretti racing family. He is the son of [[Formula 1]], CART and [[NASCAR]] racing legend [[Mario Andretti]]. His brother [[Jeff Andretti]] competed in IndyCar. Michael's uncle [[Aldo Andretti]] was an open wheel racer until an accident ended his racing career. Aldo's son, John Andretti (Michael's first cousin) raced in IndyCar before he became a NASCAR regular. He returned to IndyCar in 2007, 2008, 2009, 2010 and 2011, where he raced in the Indy 500. Aldo's other son, [[Adam Andretti|Adam]] also is a racecar driver, and in 2005, Michael's son [[Marco Andretti|Marco]] began his career in Indy Racing. The Andretti family became the first family to have five relatives (Michael, Mario, Marco, Jeff, and John) compete in the same series (CART/[[Champ Car]]/IndyCar).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/sportscentury/features/00014066.html|title=ESPN.com: Mario Andretti synonymous with racing|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n\nMichael was inducted in 2002, into [[National Italian American Sports Hall of Fame]], and he was inducted into the [[Motorsports Hall of Fame of America]] in 2008<ref name=MSHoF>[http://www.mshf.com/hall-of-fame/inductees/michael-andretti.html Michael Andretti] at the [[Motorsports Hall of Fame of America]]</ref>, the Long Beach Grand Prix Walk of Fame in 2010, the Canadian Motorsports (International Division) Hall of Fame in 2012, and the [[Indianapolis Motor Speedway Museum#Auto Racing Hall of Fame|Indianapolis Motor Speedway Hall of Fame]] in 2012.<ref name=\"andrettiautosport.com\"/>\n\n==Racing record==\n\n===Career highlights===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! Season\n! Series\n! Position\n! Team\n! Car\n|-\n| 1981\n| [[SCCA National Championship Runoffs|SCCA National Championship Runoffs Formula F]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.driverdb.com/championships/standings/scca-national-championship-runoffs-formula-f/1981/|title=SCCA National Championship Runoffs Formula F 1981 standings|publisher=Driver Database|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref>\n| 8th\n| \n| [[Van Diemen|Van Diemen RF81]]\n|-\n| 1982\n| Robert Bosch/VW Super Vee Championship<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.driverdb.com/championships/standings/formula-super-vee-usa-robert-bosch-valvoline-championship/1982/|title=Formula Super Vee USA Robert Bosch/Valvoline Championship 1982 standings|publisher=Driver Database|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oldracingcars.com/fsv/us/1982/|title=Formula Super Vee 1982|author=Allen Brown|publisher=OldRacingCars.com|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref>\n|style=\"background:#FFFFBF;\"|'''1st'''\n| [[PPI Motorsports|Arciero Racing]]\n| [[Ralt|Ralt-Volkswagen RT5/81]]<br>[[Ralt|Ralt-Volkswagen RT5/82]]\n|-\n| \n| [[SCCA National Championship Runoffs|SCCA National Championship Runoffs Formula F]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.driverdb.com/championships/standings/scca-national-championship-runoffs-formula-f/1982/|title=SCCA National Championship Runoffs Formula F 1982 standings|publisher=Driver Database|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref>\n|style=\"background:#ffdf9f;\"| 3rd \n| \n| [[Lola Cars|Lola T640]]\n|-\n| 1983\n| [[1983 Formula Atlantic season|Formula Mondial North American Cup]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.driverdb.com/championships/standings/formula-mondial-north-america/1983/|title=Formula Mondial North America 1983 standings|publisher=Driver Database|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref><ref>http://www.champcarsstats.com/atlantic/drivers/AndrettiMichael.html{{dead link|date=January 2016}}</ref>\n|style=\"background:#FFFFBF;\"|'''1st'''\n| Conte Racing\n| [[Ralt|Ralt-Ford RT4]]\n|-\n| \n| [[1983 24 Hours of Le Mans|24 Heures du Mans]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.racingsportscars.com/results/Le_Mans-1983-06-19.html|title=Le Mans 24 Hours|publisher=Racing Sports Cars|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.experiencelemans.com/contents/en-us/d154_1983_Le_Mans_24_Hours_Competitors_Results.html|title=1983 24 Hours of Le Mans Results and Competitors|publisher=Experience Le Mans|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref>\n|style=\"background:#ffdf9f;\"| 3rd \n| [[Kremer Racing]]\n| [[Porsche 956]]\n|-\n| \n| Robert Bosch/VW Super Vee Championship<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.driverdb.com/championships/standings/formula-super-vee-usa-robert-bosch-valvoline-championship/1983/|title=Formula Super Vee USA Robert Bosch/Valvoline Championship 1983 standings|publisher=Driver Database|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oldracingcars.com/fsv/us/1983/|title=Formula Super Vee 1983|author=Allen Brown|publisher=OldRacingCars.com|accessdate=July 24, 2018}}</ref>\n| 18th\n| \n| [[Ralt|Ralt-Volkswagen RT5/82]]\n|-\n| \n| [[1983 World Sportscar Championship season|FIA World Endurance Championship]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.driverdb.com/championships/standings/fia-world-endurance-championship/1983/|title=FIA World Endurance Championship 1983 standings|publisher=Driver Database|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref>\n| 25th\n| [[Kremer Racing]]\n| [[Porsche 956]]\n|-\n| \n| [[1983 CART PPG Indy Car World Series|PPG Indy Car World Series]]<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.driverdb.com/championships/standings/champ-car-world-series/1983/|title=PPG Indy Car World Series 1983 standings|publisher=Driver Database|accessdate=January 26, 